Author::::Mark Harder
DateTime::::2016-03-07T05:51:57Z
IMHO, domestic water should be tested before AND after flushing the pipes. If you flush the home's plumbing, you will be replacing the water that has been sitting in its pipes, absorbing contaminants that leach into the water slowly. Testing this water measures those contaminants and the public system's simultaneously. Emptying the home water plumbing replaces it with water from the outside, so when you test that you are only testing utility water. Doing it this latter way masks the effects of lead in your home's plumbing. The utilities don't want you to confuse your home's lead with theirs, which is a reasonable distinction for them to make. However, what the public wants to know is how much lead they are ingesting, regardless of where it came from. Both parties are happy when your water is tested under both conditions.



