Author::::Giancarlo
DateTime::::2016-03-06T17:30:49Z
This is true, and is especially a problem in older cities in the East. Many of them still use combined sewer systems because their infrastructure is so antiquated. In heavy rainfalls, water pours into storm drains and causes the system to overflow, releasing stormwater mixed with raw sewage directly into local waterways. In urban environments, the water collected by storm inlets isn't exactly clean either. It catches all of the pollutants and trash that make their way into the street: road salt, motor oil & coolant dropped by cars, small metal particles, and so on. 



